1
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:09,674
[Possibility of Impossible Love]

2
00:00:10,720 --> 00:00:13,054
Well, first of all
we should wonder

3
00:00:13,054 --> 00:00:20,384
why is it that we’re repeatedly 
expressing these things.

4
00:00:20,384 --> 00:00:26,884
In songs, in poetry, in novels, 
in motion picture, movie … everything.

5
00:00:26,884 --> 00:00:34,254
we revisit these subject matters
repeatedly.

6
00:00:34,254 --> 00:00:36,838
People find themselves
in a position

7
00:00:36,838 --> 00:00:40,770
where they’re expressing
eternal love to someone,

8
00:00:40,770 --> 00:00:47,109
when we know statistically, 
objectively speaking it’s not true.

9
00:00:47,132 --> 00:00:51,661
And mostly as time goes on
it’s more and more not true.

10
00:00:51,661 --> 00:00:54,366
We’re not sure how much
it was true before,

11
00:00:54,366 --> 00:00:57,098
but at least now that we keep records
on all this stuff,

12
00:00:57,098 --> 00:01:04,022
we know the potential
for these eternal relationships to dissolve.

13
00:01:04,022 --> 00:01:11,064
“I love you forever,
or until you’re 40.” [Laughing]

14
00:01:11,064 --> 00:01:14,294
Śrīla Avadhūt Mahārāj,
“Or untill you fat.” [Laughing]

15
00:01:14,294 --> 00:01:17,408
There are many 
different objective criteria

16
00:01:17,408 --> 00:01:23,916
that somehow destroy, 
dissolve that love,

17
00:01:23,916 --> 00:01:29,233
and we’re still hankering 
for this eternal love scenario.

18
00:01:29,649 --> 00:01:32,968
So then we think: 
then what are we doing?

19
00:01:33,338 --> 00:01:37,283
You yourself are saying 
it’s not a thing of this world.

20
00:01:37,283 --> 00:01:39,084
But stop for a second.

21
00:01:39,084 --> 00:01:43,193
We didn’t say it’s impossible
to connect with.

22
00:01:43,193 --> 00:01:47,927
We’re saying it’s not a thing 
of this objective world.

23
00:01:48,203 --> 00:01:51,864
What is expressed in those stories,
that eternal love

24
00:01:51,864 --> 00:01:54,853
that’s in the song, the story, 
the movie, etc.

25
00:01:54,853 --> 00:01:56,638
is not really a thing
of this world.

26
00:01:56,638 --> 00:01:58,211
They say, 
“No, that’s just in the movies!”

27
00:01:58,211 --> 00:01:59,809
Right.

28
00:01:59,809 --> 00:02:01,943
But does that mean
there’s not a plane where …

29
00:02:01,943 --> 00:02:07,357
it doesn’t exist anywhere.
Not even in the movies?

30
00:02:07,357 --> 00:02:12,778
No. So we understand—
we’re hardwired to seek this;

31
00:02:12,778 --> 00:02:17,628
to seek something that 
we’re trying to address

32
00:02:17,628 --> 00:02:20,603
through objective culture
in the objective …

33
00:02:20,603 --> 00:02:26,833
So it’s a purely subjective thing
that we’re trying to feed objects to.

